t's the one I need to focus on instead. The task description was written when the case was created, stating the cluster was below target version, but the actual current state shows it's already at 8.11.1. So the real work here might be fixing the corrupted password and doing a full restart to verify the upgrade process works and data stays intact. Or maybe the task is simpler—scale the StatefulSet down to zero, ensure the image is set to 8.11.1, then scale it back up to complete the full-restart upgrade.\n\nBefore I do that, I need to reset the elastic password since the adversary corrupted it. The password is stored in the Kubernetes Secret, but the running pods read it at startup, so they're still using the original password from before the Secret was changed. I need to figure out what the current actual password is in the cluster versus what's in the Secret now. was in the Secret before the adversary modified it, but I don't have visibility into what that original password was. The precondition script successfully authenticated using whatever password was stored in the Secret at that time, which means Elasticsearch accepted it. Now I'm considering whether I can reset the password directly from within the pod using Elasticsearch's built-in reset tool, which would require the cluster to be healthy and running.\n\nThe critical question is the order of operations: should I fix the password before or after doing a full restart? When Elasticsearch starts up, it only uses the ELASTIC_PASSWORD environment variable during initial bootstrap—once the cluster has started and the password is stored in the security index, subsequent restarts won't override it based on the env var. So if I restart with the corrupted password still in the environment, that won't automatically fix things.\n\nThe real problem is that the liveness and readiness probes authenticate using the current ELASTIC_PASSWORD env var value, which is corrupted, so the pods will fail their health checks. I need