{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ECsx9ofGo9hsbg2J9928Vn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! elasticsearch-0 has RESTARTS=1, with the restart happening 55 seconds ago. So the pod restarted! And the liveness probe errored because the container was in CONTAINER_EXITED state. This means the liveness probe killed the pod (due to wrong password) and it restarted.\n\nNow, elasticsearch-0 has been restarted 55 seconds ago. When it restarted, it would have read the SECRET which now has \"CORRUPTED_BY_ADVERSARY\". \n\nIn Elasticsearch 8.x Docker, when you pass ELASTIC_PASSWORD, it sets the password. \n\nBut I think this only works on first start. After that, the password is stored in the security index and the env var is ignored. Let me think through how ES 8.x actually handles password initialization: on the first bootstrap when there's no existing cluster state, it uses ELASTIC_PASSWORD to set the elastic user's password. But once the cluster has data and security indices, the environment variable gets ignored and the stored credentials take precedence. The Docker entrypoint does have logic to reset the password via the HTTP API if ELASTIC_PASSWORD is set, but I need to verify exactly how that works.\n\nThe pod restarted 55 seconds ago and is now showing READY=1/1, but when I tested with \"CORRUPTED_BY_ADVERSARY\" it returned 401. If the liveness probe is using that password and failing, the pod should eventually be killed after 15 failed attempts over 150 seconds. Either the probes somehow passed despite the auth failure, or the password actually got set to that value when the pod restarted—I should test with a fresh password to figure out what's really happening. So the password would've been reset to the corrupted value when the pod restarted, but I'm getting a 401 when I test it. I should check the Elasticsearch logs from after the restart to see what's actually happening with 