{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015nzjBDskmeeDKqNR6njjYr","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The password `elasticpass` works against elasticsearch-1 directly. But it failed against `es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200`. The `es-http` service selects all pods with `app: elasticsearch`, and some pods (elasticsearch-0 and elasticsearch-2) seem to have gotten the wrong password somehow.\n\nWait, this doesn't make sense from a security perspective. The ES password is stored in the internal `.security-7` index in the cluster, which is SHARED across all nodes. If `elasticpass` works on elasticsearch-1, it should work on all nodes.\n\nThe issue is that `es-http` is a load balancer that routes to any of the 3 elasticsearch pods. Some pods might be in an inconsistent state because:\nelasticsearch-0 restarted with CORRUPTED_BY_ADVERSARY, which could have reset the password on that pod, but the cluster-wide security index should have propagated the change to all nodes. Unless elasticsearch-0 and elasticsearch-2 aren't actually part of the same cluster as elasticsearch-1 right now. Let me check the cluster status to see if they're properly connected.\n\nActually, wait—the probe command curls localhost:9200 on each pod individually, so each node authenticates against itself. The password should be consistent across the cluster since it's stored in the distributed security index. But when I tested through es-http, which load-balances across all three pods, I got a 401. Let me try hitting it multiple times to see if this is a routing issue where some pods have a different password than others.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":418,"cache_read_input_tokens":65189,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":418},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_av