-http`. The `es-http` service selector is `app: elasticsearch`. The `elasticsearch` StatefulSet pods are already at 8.11.1. The oracle checks:\n1. Version of cluster at `es-http` → already 8.11.1 ✓\n2. Nodes in cluster at `es-http` → 5 nodes (elasticsearch-0,1,2 + es-data-new-0,1)\n3. `target_node_names` = nodes matching `_sts_name_for_node(n) == \"es-cluster\"` → NONE\n4. Falls back to all nodes = 5\n5. `expected_nodes` from `es-cluster` StatefulSet spec.replicas = 3\n6. Check: 5 != 3 → FAIL!\n\nUnless... the `es-http` service also selects `es-cluster` pods? No, it doesn't - its selector is `app: elasticsearch`. I'm realizing the `BENCH_PARAM_CLUSTER_PREFIX` environment variable is probably set to `elasticsearch` in the workflow rather than the default `es-cluster`, which would change how the oracle identifies the StatefulSet and counts nodes. If that's the case, it would be looking for pods matching `elasticsearch-*` instead.\n\nNow I need to verify what `BENCH_PARAM_CLUSTER_PREFIX` is actually set to in the workflow environment.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4757,"cache_read_input_tokens":72926,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4757},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7dfcb699-3238-4724-9d70-a60a45e29af4","uuid":"47565abd-3a67-45d0-a4f7-cd2dda133e8e","request_id":"req_011CcQe1HKNtkAYauWggtP1w"}
