{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01F11wfSNMsWDdJ1gsibSYC4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. `es-cluster` StatefulSet:\n   - Image: 7.17.9 (old version)\n   - Selector: `app: es-cluster`\n   - Labels: `app: es-cluster`\n   - Config: uses `es-transform-config` configmap\n   - Cluster name: \"es-cluster\" \n   - Uses its own headless service \"es-cluster\"\n   - NO security (xpack.security.enabled: false)\n   - Pods: CrashLoopBackOff\n\n2. `elasticsearch` StatefulSet:\n   - Image: 8.11.1 (target version) - already upgraded!\n   - Selector: `app: elasticsearch`\n   - Has security enabled (xpack.security)\n   - Pods: Running (3/3)\n\n3. `es-http` service: selector `app: elasticsearch` → points to the `elasticsearch` StatefulSet\n\nBut wait, `es-http` doesn't route to `es-cluster` pods at all, so upgrading `es-cluster` wouldn't satisfy the oracle's requirements. Let me trace through the oracle's logic again.\n\nThe oracle queries the nodes endpoint and filters for nodes belonging to the `es-cluster` StatefulSet. Currently, the nodes returned are `elasticsearch-0,1,2,es-data-new-0,es-data-new-1`, but none of these match the `es-cluster` naming pattern, so the target list comes back empty.\n\nWhen that happens, it falls back to checking all five nodes against the expected replica count of three from the StatefulSet spec—which fails since 5 ≠ 3. Additionally, the StatefulSet image check reveals the cluster is still running version 7.17.9 when it should be upgraded to 8.11.1, so that's another failure. I need to address both the node count mismatch and the image upgrade. `es-cluster-0,1,2` would show up in the nodes list, making the oracle pass since there'd be exactly 3 nodes matching the pattern. So the real problem is getting those pods to join the existing `elasticsearch` cluster instead of forming their own separate cluster.\n\nBut that's tricky because `es-cluster` is configured with a different cluster name, no security enabled, and no TLS setup, while `elasticsearch` has security turned on. They're fundamentally incompatible as-is. Maybe the actual goal here is something else entirely.\n\nLooking back at the precondition logs, the probe found 8 running pods and skipped the apply step since the environment already existed from earlier stages. So this stage is meant to upgrade the original `es-cluster` StatefulSet from version 7.17.9 to 8.11.1, and `es-http` should be routing to those upgraded `es-cluster` pods.\n\nBut I'm noticing the `es-http` service selector is `app: elasticsearch`, which targets the `elasticsearch` StatefulSet, not `es-cluster`. For the oracle to see `es-cluster-*` nodes through `es-http`, those nodes need to be part of the same cluster and properly selected by the service. I need to check whether the service definition was modified between stage_01 and the current full-restart-upgrade-ha resources, or if there's something about how the clusters are joining that I'm missing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1882,"cache_read_input_tokens":80991,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1882},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7dfcb699-3238-4724-9d70-a60a45e29af4","uuid":"bd9fdbc2-d287-4df5-893f-0d31b78fa3bf","request_id":"req_011CcQe5gD9P12MXYuN7t4mo"}
