{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01N9tgQiummxtqmG2KP7izhb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now the whole picture is clear!\n\nThe deploy-core-cluster precondition:\n- On apply: deletes the namespace and recreates it\n- Creates TLS certs\n- Sets password to \"elasticpass\"\n- The AGENT (stage_01) then deploys the Elasticsearch cluster\n\nSince the probe found pods running (from a previous workflow run), the apply was SKIPPED in the workflow context. The `elasticsearch` StatefulSet was deployed by the AGENT in stage_01 to fulfill the deploy-core-cluster task. \n\nHOWEVER, the `es-cluster` StatefulSet at 7.17.9 - WHERE DID IT COME FROM? It was applied by someone BEFORE this run (the `kubectl.kubernetes.io/last-applied-configuration` shows a 7.17.9 image). \n\nNow I'm looking at what the stage_05 oracle actually needs. The `es-http` service selector points to `app: elasticsearch`, so when it queries the version endpoint it gets 8.11.1, and when it fetches the nodes it gets all 5 from the `elasticsearch` cluster. But when it tries to find nodes matching the `es-cluster-*` pattern, there are none, so it falls back to using all available nodes.\n\nThe problem is that `expected_nodes` comes from the `es-cluster` StatefulSet replica count, which is 3. So the oracle compares 5 actual nodes against 3 expected and fails. For the oracle to pass, either the `es-cluster-*` nodes need to actually join the `elasticsearch` cluster so they show up in the node list, or I need to change how the service discovery works. them. The `es-http` service points to the `elasticsearch` cluster, so for `es-cluster-0,1,2` to show up in the node list, they need to actually join that cluster. Looking at how `es-data-new` successfully joined, it's configured with `cluster.name: elasticsearch` and the proper node roles and network settings.\n\nThe key difference is that `es-data-new` also has discovery seed hosts pointing