{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Ua8YoVnCTB2KEDqUACtv8m","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The crash reason is clear: `xpack.security.enrollment.enabled` is not a valid setting in Elasticsearch 7.17.9. It's an 8.x setting. The `es-cluster` pods are using the `es-config` ConfigMap which has settings for 8.x, but the image is 7.17.9.\n\nSo the fix is:\n1. Upgrade `es-cluster` image from 7.17.9 to 8.11.1\n2. Add TLS certs volume to `es-cluster` StatefulSet (cert files are needed for 8.x security)\n3. Add ELASTIC_PASSWORD env var (from elastic-password secret)\n4. Do a full restart by scaling to 0 then back to 3\n\nThe `es-config` ConfigMap already has the right settings for joining the `elasticsearch` cluster. I need to check whether the node names will conflict—the `es-cluster` pods will get hostnames like `es-cluster-0`, `es-cluster-1`, `es-cluster-2`, which should be distinct from the existing `elasticsearch-0,1,2` nodes.\n\nThe `cluster.initial_master_nodes` setting in `es-config` will just trigger a warning since the cluster is already formed with a UUID, and the new nodes will join as non-bootstrap nodes. I'm also verifying which ConfigMap the `es-cluster` StatefulSet actually uses—checking the volume mounts shows it's pulling from `es-config`, not `es-transform-config`.\n\nSince `es-config` doesn't explicitly set `node.roles`, the `es-cluster-*` pods will get all roles by default (master-eligible, data, ingest), which works fine for joining the existing cluster. Now I'm planning the patch strategy: update the `es-cluster` StatefulSet with the new image version, add the password environment variable and TLS certificates, then perform a full restart by scaling to zero and back up.\n\nI notice the current StatefulSet uses `RollingUpdate` strategy, but since the task requires a full stop-and-start upgrade, I'll need to scale down to 0 first, then scale back to 3 and wait for all pods to be ready and rejoin the cluster.\n\nWriting kubectl patch commands... Writing kubectl commands... Configuring TLS settings...\n\nAll nodes share the same certificates from the secret, so they'll trust each other through the CA. The plan should work—I'll scale the StatefulSet to 0 to clear the failing pods, then back up to 3 with the updated spec. With the RollingUpdate strategy, I need to be careful about how the rollout happens. The `es-http` service selector will still work fine since the new `es-cluster` pods will join the existing Elasticsearch cluster and appear in the `/_cat/nodes` response. However, I need to consider whether the 7.x data directories in the existing PVCs are compatible with 8.x, as the data format might cause startup issues.\n\nSince the `es-cluster` pods have been stuck in CrashLoopBackOff for the past 37 minutes trying to run 7.17.9 with 8.x configuration settings, they likely never successfully wrote any data. The PVCs are probably empty or contain only partial state from a previous run, so when 8.11.1 starts up, it should either bootstrap as new nodes joining the cluster or attempt recovery depending on what's actually on disk.\n\nThe `cluster.initial_master_nodes` setting in the configmap only matters during initial bootstrap anyway, so it won't interfere with joining an existing cluster. There's a potential risk if the nodes have a stored cluster UUID from a previous successful 7.x run, but given they've been crashing continuously since creation, there's likely no persistent state to worry about.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3254,"cache_read_input_tokens":87978,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3254},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7dfcb699-3238-4724-9d70-a60a4