{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Vy1vvpLhjivUuGjS2jKhpR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So \"elasticpass\" works SOMETIMES (3/5 attempts) and returns 401 other times. This is consistent with the load balancer routing to different pods:\n- `elasticsearch-1`: 0 restarts, old env `ELASTIC_PASSWORD=elasticpass`, and the cluster's internal password matches \"elasticpass\" → 200\n- `elasticsearch-0`: 1 restart, started with `ELASTIC_PASSWORD=CORRUPTED_BY_ADVERSARY` → might have changed the internal password\n- `elasticsearch-2`: 0 restarts but env shows `CORRUPTED_BY_ADVERSARY` (it ALSO restarted at some point)\nWait, there's something off here. If elasticsearch-2 started with `ELASTIC_PASSWORD=CORRUPTED_BY_ADVERSARY` and its readiness probe passes, that means the cluster password is actually \"CORRUPTED_BY_ADVERSARY\". But then elasticsearch-1's probe should be failing since it's using \"elasticpass\"—unless elasticsearch-1 somehow has a different password than the rest of the cluster, which doesn't make sense for a coordinated cluster. The probe should fail if the cluster password is still \"elasticpass\", but elasticsearch-2 shows ready despite having CORRUPTED_BY_ADVERSARY in its env. This suggests either the security index password got updated to match the corrupted value when that pod restarted, or there's something else allowing the probe to pass. If that happened, elasticsearch-1 would still work because it's connecting with the same password that's now in the cluster security index.\n\nBut wait—if the password changed to CORRUPTED_BY_ADVERSARY, then elasticsearch-1's probe using \"elasticpass\" should be failing now. The pod shows ready, which means either the password hasn't actually changed yet, or the pod hasn't had time to fail the readiness checks enough times to become unready. Given the failureThreshold is 15 checks at 10-second intervals, that's 150 seconds of failures before the pod gets marked unready. Since elasticsearch-1 is 19 minutes old with no restarts, I need to check its actual current readiness status to see if it's already failing those probes. So elasticsearch-1 should fail its probe since it's still using the old password while the cluster password changed, but it's showing as ready after 19 minutes—that doesn't add up. Let me directly test what passwords are actually working to figure out what's going on.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1433,"cache_read_input_tokens":105876,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1433},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7dfcb699-3238-4724-9d70-a60a45e29af4","uuid":"012c8823-16db-4a4f-9be5-1470bb83636c","request_id":"req_011CcQeiVEshsTmKLWFny4HB"}
