{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0169MPkyi9DdpLXAYFw1Zth7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Very interesting!\n\n- `elasticsearch-0`: NOT reachable at all (exit code 6 = DNS/connection failure). The pod must have just crashed or is in the process of restarting.\n- `elasticsearch-1`: \"elasticpass\" works (200), \"CORRUPTED_BY_ADVERSARY\" fails (401)\n- `elasticsearch-2`: \"elasticpass\" fails (401), \"CORRUPTED_BY_ADVERSARY\" works (200)\n\nThis is bizarre - two different nodes in the same cluster have different passwords? That should be impossible if they're in the same cluster (shared security index).\n\nUnless... `elasticsearch-2` is not actually in the same cluster but has the same headless service somehow? No, I saw it in `/_cat/nodes` from elasticsearch-1.\n \nOr maybe when a pod restarts, it re-reads its keystore and config, and `elasticsearch-2` somehow picked up different credentials. But that still doesn't explain why `elasticsearch-1` would accept \"elasticpass\" if the cluster's security index was overwritten. I'm wondering if there could be multiple security realms at play here - maybe different users or realm configurations on each node that I'm not seeing.\n\nActually, the most likely culprit is probably incomplete replication of the security index. When `elasticsearch-2` restarted and corrupted its state, the security index shards might not have fully replicated across the cluster yet, leaving different nodes with different views of the password state.\n\nBut I should check the current pod status first—`elasticsearch-0` appears to have crashed again (exit code 6), which could mean the master node is down and the cluster is destabilizing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1598,"cache_read_input_tokens":107309,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_inp